{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Two New York cases illustrate the uncertainty attending judicial (or prosecutorial) attempts to monitor mission fidelity under the current state of the law. First, Littauer v. Spitzer involved a merger, driven by financial exigencies, between a secular and a Catholic hospital, each of which were controlled by parents; the merger was accomplished by transferring control of both hospitals to a common parent, which itself became a joint subsidiary of the original parents.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F77303574216_ID0EG5AG_2}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F77303574216_ID0EG5AG_2}
