{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0EBUBG_2}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0EBUBG_2}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Close examination of the structure and economics of the nonprofit firm exposes paradoxes in extending corporate principles to charitable corporations. First and most fundamentally, the nonprofit faces greater obstacles in overcoming agency costs than its for-profit counterparts because it lacks residual claimants. The ability of the capital market to monitor and police the actions of managers in the for-profit sector is generally acknowledged.
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F131303574216_ID0EPUBG_2}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F131303574216_ID0EPUBG_2}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F131303574216_2" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
131
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Interested shareholders can also serve those functions through the mechanisms of corporate democracy, including election of directors, proxy contests and other means of shareholder \u8220\'3factivism.\u8221\'3f However, because the principal of the nonprofit corporation is not readily identifiable, there is no claimant with sufficient incentives to monitor agents\rquote  abuses. Further, even if some altruists were willing to act as monitors, existing legal regimes provide few direct remedies for abuses.
}
