A second factor undermining the efficacy of fiduciary law in nonprofit corporations is that their goals are multi-faceted and often not well-defined. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
While managers of business corporations must strictly observe the over-arching objective of profit maximization, their nonprofit counterparts face a more complex array of goals. Although generating net income is surely an important objective (especially in commercial not-for-profit organizations), it is also necessary to simultaneously accommodate the other, competing objectives of the organization articulated in the mission. Thus, nonprofit managers and directors must reconcile business objectives and mission. Complicating the task further is the fact that the mission objectives are often stated in general terms that lack the precise, quantifiable frame posed by the profit maximization standard.
