{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
We have also seen that the role of mission in informing directors\rquote  decision-making is quite ambiguous. When assessing whether boards have satisfied their fiduciary responsibilities, courts and charity regulators sometimes invoke mission responsibilities, and sometimes ignore them. For example, the MEETH and Littauer decisions send mixed messages about boards\rquote  autonomy to interpret and direct their mission in New York. 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
