{\b1 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa200 \sb200 
V. Conclusion: A Proposal for Mission Primacy
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E1LCI_2}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E1LCI_2}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Our review of the application of fiduciary and charitable trust law to nonprofit health care corporations has identified a number of significant problems. First, there is widespread confusion about the boundaries between those bodies of law. Difficulties are compounded by the impact of those laws on the health sector--notably the uneasy fit of importing wholesale for-profit corporate principles to govern entities having decidedly different attributes and goals, and the inappropriateness of using rigid trust concepts to guide management of dynamic commercial enterprises. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This confusion has led to opportunism among certain attorneys general who have sought judicial relief, which inappropriately transfers power over business and mission decisions to them. It has also 
}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
{\*\bkmkstart co_pp_sp_155362_81_2}{\*\bkmkend co_pp_sp_155362_81_2}
{\b1 \cf1 \f2 \i0 \fs20 
