{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The failure of courts and commentators to resolve questions of ownership and mission accountability is in part explained by the plurality of competing interests. Starting with the perspective that tax expenditures and legal support create a strong public entitlement, some regard the public at large (or its representative) as the appropriate locus of accountability. Others identify as the appropriate party in interest the beneficiaries of the nonprofit\rquote s charitable mission. Still others advocate including the \u8220\'3fpatrons\u8221\'3f--donors and customers who provide the financial wherewithal to fulfilling the nonprofit\rquote s charitable mission. Finally, there is the perspective of the \u8220\'3fsponsor\u8221\'3f or \u8220\'3fmember\u8221\'3f of the nonprofit corporation, whose control and support keep the enterprise running. Choosing among these competing parties in interest is ultimately a normative and political question that underlies any workable definition of \u8220\'3faccountability.\u8221\'3f As Evelyn Brody framed the issue: \u8220\'3fWho are the \u8216\'3fprincipals\rquote  to whom society wants the charity to answer . . . ?\u8221\'3f
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \i0 \fs16 
{\*\bkmkstart co_fnRef_F289303574216_ID0EUSCI_2}{\*\bkmkend co_fnRef_F289303574216_ID0EUSCI_2}
{\field {\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "#co_footnote_F289303574216_2" }{\fldrslt 
{\super \b0 \cf22 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs16 \sa0 \sb0 
289
}}}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 Like many before us, we will dodge that question. Instead we offer a framework for allowing courts and legislatures to address the issue by allocating presumptive decisionmaking authority to those entrusted with serving the nonprofit\rquote s purposes, but insisting that they follow clearly articulated mission statements.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs20 \li0 
