{\*\bkmkstart co_g_ID0E1WCI_2}{\*\bkmkend co_g_ID0E1WCI_2}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
This Article counsels strongly against states\rquote  reliance on charitable trust law to regulate nonprofit assets, except, of course, where an express trust exists. We have argued that applying charitable trust law to corporate assets is doctrinally unsound and produces outcomes that potentially waste, rather than preserve, scarce charitable assets. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
The alternative approach, adopted by most of the courts to have directly addressed the issue, is to look to corporate law as the foundation for the law governing all aspects of charitable corporations. While this reflects our preferred doctrinal path, recognition of the mission primacy principle proposed above is necessary to assure that both boards and charity regulators observe core nonprofit purposes.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
