{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
Viewed from the perspective of health care policy, the most important--and most vexing--public policy question emanating from our analysis of charitable nonprofit law is how the law can best achieve the appropriate distribution of health care resources. These concerns undoubtedly drive attorneys general to undertake many of the actions for which we take them to task in this Article. Simply stated, the problem we identify in this regard is one of institutional competence and transparency. To the extent that there are market failures, there are alternative and more focused means of regulation and allocation including licensure, certificate of need regulation, and subsidies from state departments of 
}
