{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs20 \sa0 \sb0 
 health; exercise of the state\rquote s tax-exemption powers; and contracting by state entities funding health services. Without expressing a preference for any particular regulatory regime, we believe that policy-making through these agencies is preferable because it is more likely to identify and evaluate deficits in safety net services. By contrast, allocating broad and unrestricted discretion to attorneys general to make allocative decisions behind a veil of corporate or charitable trust litigation appears to be a recipe for ad hoc and inefficient decision-making.
