The complex AHERF organization was governed by a parent board consisting of no fewer than thirty-five members. Ten other boards, having little overlapping membership, governed fifty-five corporations; each board was generally unaware of what other parts of the system were doing. Directors were chosen and dominated by Mr. Abdelhak and board meetings were, according to one analysis, \u8220\'3fscripted affairs, intentionally staged to limit oversight and participation by board members.... [M]embers... receive as many as 1,000 pages of paper to be discussed at board meetings.... As one former member explained, \u8216\'3fHalf of the people didn\rquote t even open the book. They didn\rquote t have the time.\u8221\'3f\u8217\'3f Lawton R. Burns et al., The Fall of the House of AHERF: The Allegheny Bankruptcy, 19 Health Aff. 7, 21 (2000). Although the AHERF boards consisted of top-notch executives, all were extremely busy and unable to perform a broad oversight responsibility over the organization. In addition, the bylaws permitted many key decisions to be made by Mr. Abdelhak. Id.
\par 
