A recent account by one of AHERF\rquote s insiders that is highly critical of top management explains that the Boards were supplied with extensive information, perhaps so much so that they were unable to digest it and properly supervise management.
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
It might be reasonable to suppose that the [AHERF] trustees were unable to see and perhaps prevent the oncoming train wreck because they were underinformed. In fact, nothing could be further from the truth. The trustees of the constituent corporations of HERF and of AHERF itself were regularly given reams of information, including detailed financial statements. Although it would have taken a reader of financials with extraordinary insight to discern from one of the constituent corporation\rquote s statements how all of AHERF was doing, there was enough crossover on the various boards that there was a core of trustees who had most if not all of the relevant information available to them. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
The more likely scenario, in fact is that the trustees had too much information; they were given so much to absorb that they could not winnow out what was important.
\par 
}
}
}
