According to MEETH:
\par 
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
Not-for-profit corporations operate under legal regimes designed for traditional for-profit corporations. 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa200 \sb0 
However, fundamental structural differences between not-for-profit corporations and for-profit corporations render this approach incapable of providing effective internal mechanisms to guard against directors\rquote  improvident use of charitable assets. For example, in the for-profit context, shareholder power ensures that Boards make provident decisions, while in the not-for-profit context, this internal check does not exist. To put it another way, a nonprofit corporation has no \u8220\'3fowners\u8221\'3f or private parties with a pecuniary stake to monitor and scrutinize actions by the directors.
\par 
}
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f2 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
